ratings.question_text: What is your overall assessment of this course?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 for a fellow student? Would you recommend AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Wonderful seminar for anyone who is interested in critically engaging with Nothing(s), as it has emerged alongside Western philosophical and literary history. I would definitely recommend the course to anyone interested in these questions.

A course on the idea of Nothing in western history of philosophy. Some of the texts are very, very challenging. And like its title, you might very possibly feel you got nothing out of it at the end of the semester. But take this course nevertheless, just for the sake of getting to know prof. North and start thinking about nothing in different ways, if you are interested in fundamental philosophical questions.

narratives.question_text: How did this course deepen your knowledge of your discipline/profession? To what extent did this course contribute to your dissertation/research?
comments: I am an undergraduate philosophy major, and this course helped me to improve my skills in close reading philosophical texts.
Profoundly so--"Nothing" is crucial for my research.
I got to know that I want to pursue philosophy with the guidance of texts like those discussed in this course and people like prof. North...
